text.tspan: is the change in allele frequency caused by sampling genes
at random from one generation to the next
Six different populations of 100 gene copies each. Each trial starts with two
alleles in 50-50 proportions. Then, genes are sampled randomly to form the
next generation. Repeat until one allele or the other has reached 100 percent...
Sometimes the population fixes quickly, sometimes more slowly.
Sometimes one allele goes to 100 percent, sometimes it goes to zero.
The variation in these outcomes reflects the random sampling.
